206
00:26:22,965 --> 00:26:24,523
<i>I like her.</i>

207
00:26:26,094 --> 00:26:27,322
<i>She's a Protestant.</i>

208
00:26:28,347 --> 00:26:29,985
<i>A Baptist, I think</i>

209
00:26:30,892 --> 00:26:33,087
Were you baptized in a river?

210
00:26:35,064 --> 00:26:36,656
What happened?

211
00:26:38,944 --> 00:26:40,172
Well...

212
00:26:43,742 --> 00:26:45,539
Is it a secret?

213
00:26:47,539 --> 00:26:49,769
We gathered by the river...

214
00:26:50,209 --> 00:26:55,363
...the pastor and I entered the water
and he told me the meaning of baptism.

215
00:26:56,509 --> 00:27:00,627
For us, baptism symbolizes
the death of sin...

216
00:27:02,183 --> 00:27:06,699
<i>... the resurrection of a new life,
full of faith, hope and dignity.</i>

217
00:27:10,152 --> 00:27:12,188
<i>Then he immersed me in the water.</i>

218
00:27:12,614 --> 00:27:17,369
<i>You've no idea how frightened I was.</i>

219
00:27:20,499 --> 00:27:22,888
<i>But it was all over so quickly.</i>

220
00:27:23,878 --> 00:27:26,676
<i>All that worry and fuss for nothing.</i>

221
00:28:36,891 --> 00:28:39,121
<i>Almost everyone's an exhibitionist.</i>

222
00:28:40,562 --> 00:28:45,761
<i>I see people as weak, almost
hairless animals, on two legs.</i>

223
00:28:48,572 --> 00:28:51,040
<i>Someone said that man's intelligence
and physical imperfection...</i>

224
00:28:51,493 --> 00:28:53,802
<i>...are because he's the premature
foetus of a monkey.</i>

225
00:29:14,648 --> 00:29:16,400
<i>At an exquisite moment...</i>

226
00:29:16,818 --> 00:29:21,209
<i>... between 30 and 35, Cuban women
lose their looks.</i>

227
00:29:24,036 --> 00:29:27,312
<i>They are fruits which rot
at an amazing speed.</i>

228
00:29:36,719 --> 00:29:39,233
<i>The rule of the Yankee empire...</i>

229
00:29:39,681 --> 00:29:44,357
<i>... having been ended by the
triumph of the Revolution...</i>

230
00:29:44,896 --> 00:29:48,013
<i>... their Guantanamo Base
is now a spy centre.</i>

231
00:29:48,568 --> 00:29:50,559
<i>Our cameramen...</i>

232
00:29:50,987 --> 00:29:53,979
<i>... film some of the provocations...</i>

233
00:29:54,409 --> 00:29:58,641
<i>... by military personnel and
counter-revolutionaries hiding there.</i>

234
00:30:32,667 --> 00:30:34,658
You have beautiful knees.

235
00:31:15,181 --> 00:31:17,741
- Will you have dinner with me?
- Are you crazy?

236
00:31:18,060 --> 00:31:20,255
No, I just don't like eating alone.

237
00:31:27,113 --> 00:31:31,470
Are you waiting for someone?
Your boyfriend?

238
00:31:34,415 --> 00:31:35,768
Are you crazy?

239
00:31:37,961 --> 00:31:40,919
Iùs dangerous to wait around alone
at your age.

240
00:31:42,926 --> 00:31:44,518
You are crazy.

241
00:31:44,845 --> 00:31:46,961
No, look... really...

242
00:31:52,981 --> 00:31:57,133
Why not have dinner? I get
indigestion if I eat alone.

243
00:31:57,528 --> 00:32:03,478
I'm waiting for someone from the
film company. I'm having a film test.

244
00:32:03,953 --> 00:32:07,582
I have a friend there. An important
director, I believe.

245
00:32:07,958 --> 00:32:09,311
In the film company?

246
00:32:09,586 --> 00:32:11,975
I'll introduce you to him,
if you like.

247
00:32:13,758 --> 00:32:16,318
- What'ùs the time?
- About six-thirty.

248
00:32:19,056 --> 00:32:21,206
He's late. He won't come now.

249
00:32:42,170 --> 00:32:43,967
Won't you have a drink?

250
00:32:44,298 --> 00:32:48,416
I mustn't. I'm having injections
for my nerves.

251
00:33:03,740 --> 00:33:05,537
Why do you want to act?

252
00:33:05,909 --> 00:33:08,139
I'm tired of always being the same.

253
00:33:09,831 --> 00:33:13,301
I want to be someone different
without people thinking I'm crazy.

254
00:33:13,669 --> 00:33:16,788
I want to develop my personality.

255
00:33:17,383 --> 00:33:20,739
But all those characters
are like scratched records.

256
00:33:21,221 --> 00:33:24,577
An actress just keeps
repeating everything.

257
00:33:24,976 --> 00:33:30,926
The same movements, the same words,
thousands of times.

258
00:35:01,018 --> 00:35:03,134
Where did you get them?

259
00:35:03,438 --> 00:35:07,795
We found them. They're cuts
made by the old censor.

260
00:35:08,194 --> 00:35:10,833
The outfit we had before
the Revolution.

261
00:35:11,157 --> 00:35:14,115
They refused to pass such scenes.

262
00:35:14,494 --> 00:35:18,169
They said they offended morals
and good taste.

263
00:35:22,213 --> 00:35:26,001
So they had their moral
preoccupations, too.

264
00:35:27,011 --> 00:35:29,241
At least they worried about
keeping up a front.

265
00:35:31,183 --> 00:35:34,459
- What will you do with them?
- I might use them.

266
00:35:35,522 --> 00:35:39,197
As a sort of collage,
a bit of everything.

267
00:35:39,610 --> 00:35:43,489
- It will need to have some meaning.
- It will. You'll see.

268
00:35:44,116 --> 00:35:45,993
Will they release it?

269
00:35:52,753 --> 00:35:57,031
Have you acted before? In the
theatre, or on television?

270
00:35:57,425 --> 00:35:59,302
No, I had no luck.

271
00:35:59,595 --> 00:36:01,551
Have you studied drama?

272
00:36:02,891 --> 00:36:05,928
Well, I did intend to
take some classes...

273
00:36:06,437 --> 00:36:09,588
Well, just complete that form.

274
00:36:11,235 --> 00:36:13,795
Aren't you going to audition me?

275
00:36:14,990 --> 00:36:16,662
I can sing, too.

276
00:36:35,058 --> 00:36:37,936
If you say so... Well?

277
00:36:39,647 --> 00:36:41,365
Are you sure iùs no?

278
00:36:42,777 --> 00:36:46,087
What a beautiful house.
Do you like it?

279
00:36:56,503 --> 00:36:58,380
Don't think we'll do anything.

280
00:37:22,871 --> 00:37:25,988
That'ùs where I live. Come on.

281
00:37:30,047 --> 00:37:32,038
- I don't...
- Don't what?

282
00:37:33,009 --> 00:37:35,967
- What about your wife?
- I told you, I'm divorced.

283
00:37:36,347 --> 00:37:40,545
- Even so, what about the neighbours?
- Well, if you don't trust me...

284
00:37:41,896 --> 00:37:43,534
What'ùs wrong then?

285
00:37:45,984 --> 00:37:48,339
Well, you go up first.

286
00:37:49,197 --> 00:37:51,836
Top floor, apartment K-L.

287
00:39:07,257 --> 00:39:11,136
Make yourself at home.
I'll make some coffee.

288
00:39:55,904 --> 00:39:59,453
My parents... and my ex-wife, Laura.

289
00:40:01,036 --> 00:40:02,913
They left on the same day.

290
00:40:06,084 --> 00:40:07,358
And you?

291
00:40:11,550 --> 00:40:13,029
Aren't you leaving?

292
00:40:13,302 --> 00:40:16,180
No, I'm all right here.

293
00:40:20,687 --> 00:40:22,564
Are you a revolutionary?

294
00:40:24,692 --> 00:40:26,250
What do you think?

295
00:40:28,614 --> 00:40:31,412
Neither revolutionary
nor counter-revolutionary.

296
00:40:32,160 --> 00:40:34,037
Well, what am I?

297
00:40:35,289 --> 00:40:37,325
You're nothing.

298
00:40:49,975 --> 00:40:52,933
- They'll send you things.
- What for?

299
00:40:55,983 --> 00:40:59,862
They could send nice shoes...
maybe even a car.

300
00:41:04,411 --> 00:41:06,720
Laura had a figure like yours

301
00:41:09,793 --> 00:41:12,261
You can look at her dresses

302
00:41:13,631 --> 00:41:16,145
You can have them, if you like.

303
00:41:23,602 --> 00:41:25,672
Look at them, anyway.

304
00:41:41,459 --> 00:41:42,414
Perfect!

305
00:41:49,803 --> 00:41:51,714
You must fasten it up.

306
00:44:22,044 --> 00:44:24,433
Come along now, don't cry.

307
00:44:31,974 --> 00:44:33,612
You've ruined me.

308
00:44:43,781 --> 00:44:46,898
We've done nothing wrong.

309
00:44:47,286 --> 00:44:49,242
What shall I tell mama?

310
00:44:50,999 --> 00:44:53,467
Don't tell her anything.

311
00:45:35,265 --> 00:45:37,620
I'll come with you if you like.

312
00:45:39,771 --> 00:45:42,239
No thanks, I'd rather be alone.

313
00:45:53,247 --> 00:45:54,805
Call me.

314
00:46:28,001 --> 00:46:32,631
<i>Thanks to such things you're
no longer a slovenly Cuban girl.</i>

315
00:46:33,341 --> 00:46:36,856
I never know whether you're
serious or joking.

316
00:46:37,221 --> 00:46:38,256
A little of both.

317
00:46:38,515 --> 00:46:40,904
Go joke to your mother!

318
00:46:46,609 --> 00:46:51,637
I can't stand living here
any longer! You stink!

319
00:46:58,332 --> 00:47:00,800
Everything you said was recorded.

320
00:47:01,545 --> 00:47:05,857
Every word. I'ùll be fun when
you hear it played back.

321
00:47:06,510 --> 00:47:09,820
You monster! I'll smash
the recorder!

322
00:47:17,900 --> 00:47:21,609
Let me go! I never want to
see you again!

323
00:47:26,160 --> 00:47:30,870
I'm leaving... alone. I don't
want you to come with me.

324
00:47:31,292 --> 00:47:32,566
Leave me?

325
00:47:32,836 --> 00:47:36,067
Find some other woman,
more to your taste!

326
00:47:36,924 --> 00:47:40,234
I won't be a guinea pig for
your whims and games!

327
00:47:40,596 --> 00:47:45,875
I'm going to live my own life!
I'm getting old!

328
00:47:46,771 --> 00:47:51,970
I don't want to be with you!
I'm leaving!

329
00:48:29,159 --> 00:48:32,037
<i>Before your lips confirmed
you loved me...</i>

330
00:48:32,414 --> 00:48:35,690
<i>... I already knew it, I knew it!</i>

331
00:48:37,712 --> 00:48:38,701
All right now?

332
00:48:40,382 --> 00:48:42,338
I thought you felt bad.

333
00:48:42,635 --> 00:48:46,833
I'm all right now. I'll help you
prepare lunch, if you like.

334
00:48:52,023 --> 00:48:54,981
- What'ùs the matter?
- Nothing's the matter with me.

335
00:49:02,453 --> 00:49:05,763
<i>Go, say it! It couldn't last!</i>

336
00:49:06,125 --> 00:49:11,916
<i>Iùs all over! You don't love me
any more!</i>

337
00:49:18,474 --> 00:49:19,907
Nice?

338
00:49:20,185 --> 00:49:22,141
Why did you cry last night?

339
00:49:22,479 --> 00:49:24,595
- Don't make fun of me.
- I'm not.

340
00:49:24,899 --> 00:49:27,333
You are, you don't have any feelings.

341
00:49:27,653 --> 00:49:30,725
<i>You don't have to criticize
the way I live...</i>

342
00:49:35,913 --> 00:49:38,473
<i>One thing about people
that upsets me...</i>

343
00:49:38,876 --> 00:49:42,425
<i>... is their inability to sustain
something without collapsing.</i>

344
00:49:44,425 --> 00:49:45,574
<i>Take Elena...</i>

345
00:49:46,552 --> 00:49:48,543
<i>... she was totally inconsistent.</i>

346
00:49:49,932 --> 00:49:51,126
<i>Didn't relate things.</i>

347
00:49:52,769 --> 00:49:54,964
<i>Thaùs a symptom of underdevelopment.</i>

348
00:49:55,481 --> 00:49:59,793
<i>The inability to relate things,
to gain experience, develop.</i>

349
00:50:02,699 --> 00:50:04,655
<i>Iùs difficult here...</i>

350
00:50:05,035 --> 00:50:08,823
<i>... because women are conditioned
by sentiments and culture.</i>

351
00:50:09,666 --> 00:50:14,535
<i>A soft environment. People waste
talents on inconsistent adaptations.</i>

352
00:50:16,258 --> 00:50:19,056
<i>They always need someone
to think for them.</i>

353
00:50:23,893 --> 00:50:26,612
I hope to see you soon, Sergio.

354
00:50:28,691 --> 00:50:31,410
No, I'm already familiar with
the States.

355
00:50:31,737 --> 00:50:34,012
What will happen here is the mystery.

356
00:50:34,448 --> 00:50:37,201
Everyone knows what will happen.

357
00:50:37,578 --> 00:50:39,773
Well, I don't. I really don't.

358
00:50:40,581 --> 00:50:43,379
It won't be like the Bay of Pigs.

359
00:50:44,587 --> 00:50:47,977
Maybe not, but it might have
interesting results.

360
00:50:48,342 --> 00:50:51,140
Right, but I'd rather be
on the other side.

361
00:50:52,180 --> 00:50:53,932
You'll be safer.

362
00:50:55,267 --> 00:50:57,497
And you'll be able to see old friends.

363
00:50:57,812 --> 00:51:02,840
I know what you mean, but there are
decent people among them.

364
00:51:03,737 --> 00:51:05,409
So they say.

365
00:51:05,739 --> 00:51:09,414
Whatever they say, I've got
a clear conscience.

366
00:51:11,372 --> 00:51:12,566
You, yes.

367
00:51:24,931 --> 00:51:26,808
<i>Was I like him?</i>

368
00:51:28,561 --> 00:51:29,835
<i>Possibly.</i>

369
00:51:31,189 --> 00:51:36,468
<i>The Revolution is my revenge on
idiots like Pablo, at my own risk.</i>

370
00:51:43,289 --> 00:51:46,486
<i>I know Pablo isn't Pablo,
he's my own life.</i>

371
00:51:46,960 --> 00:51:48,871
<i>Everything I don't want to be.</i>

372
00:51:50,214 --> 00:51:51,772
<i>Good riddance.</i>

373
00:51:52,175 --> 00:51:53,927
<i>Like vomiting them up.</i>

374
00:51:55,680 --> 00:51:59,389
<i>I keep my mind clear.
A disagreeable emptiness.</i>

375
00:52:00,561 --> 00:52:05,191
<i>I can't prevent whaùs happening
to me: Him, Laura, everyone.</i>

376
00:52:26,303 --> 00:52:28,339
<i>Francisco de la Cuesta lived here.</i>

377
00:52:33,062 --> 00:52:35,622
<i>We were eight or ten years old.</i>

378
00:52:37,526 --> 00:52:39,437
<i>Where is Francisco now?</i>

379
00:52:44,035 --> 00:52:46,071
<i>Does he remember our pranks?</i>

380
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:50,956
<i>I try to and I can't.</i>

381
00:53:17,662 --> 00:53:20,620
<i>At school the priests were
always right.</i>

382
00:53:21,584 --> 00:53:23,176
<i>They had the power.</i>

383
00:53:24,254 --> 00:53:25,448
<i>I'd done nothing...</i>

384
00:53:26,924 --> 00:53:29,233
<i>Then I understood the relationship
of Justice and Power.</i>

385
00:53:34,017 --> 00:53:36,975
<i>Armando's father was a freethinker.</i>

386
00:53:37,313 --> 00:53:41,909
<i>Every week he'd give him a peso
to go to a brothel.</i>

387
00:53:45,323 --> 00:53:49,760
<i>He took me to a woman who charged
50 cents; told her to be nice to me.</i>

388
00:54:34,346 --> 00:54:36,462
<i>But I couldn't do anything with her.</i>

389
00:54:39,102 --> 00:54:40,455
<i>I had to find another.</i>

390
00:54:46,862 --> 00:54:49,376
<i>After that I went every week.</i>

391
00:54:56,041 --> 00:54:59,920
<i>Suddenly I discovered that Elena
didn't think like me.</i>

392
00:55:01,339 --> 00:55:05,651
<i>I expected more of her. I thought
she was complex and interesting.</i>

393
00:55:07,347 --> 00:55:08,621
<i>I'm Europeanized.</i>

394
00:55:10,059 --> 00:55:13,176
<i>Elena forces me to feel
underdeveloped.</i>

395
00:55:28,583 --> 00:55:31,780
<i>I tried to change Elena,
but, like Laura...</i>

396
00:55:32,756 --> 00:55:37,955
<i>... she doesn't understand, she has
a different world in her head.</i>

397
00:55:39,431 --> 00:55:40,864
<i>She doesn't see me.</i>

398
00:55:47,441 --> 00:55:49,955
A TROPICAL ADVENTURE

399
00:55:50,279 --> 00:55:54,431
Hemingway shot this gazelle
on his last trip to Africa.

400
00:55:56,620 --> 00:55:59,088
That was in 1953.

401
00:56:01,084 --> 00:56:03,882
He made that trip with Mary,
his fourth wife.

402
00:56:09,846 --> 00:56:13,634
It is one of the fastest
gazelles in Africa.

403
00:56:25,825 --> 00:56:28,214
<i>He said he killed it to avoid
killing himself.</i>

404
00:56:30,039 --> 00:56:32,109
<i>But finally he couldn't resist
the temptation.</i>

405
00:56:42,263 --> 00:56:44,902
He made several trips to Spain
as war correspondent...

406
00:57:05,836 --> 00:57:08,270
Is this where Mr. Way used to live?

407
00:57:12,261 --> 00:57:15,890
What'ùs special about it?
Books and dead animals.

408
00:57:18,769 --> 00:57:21,567
Just like the American houses
in Preston.

409
00:57:22,691 --> 00:57:26,240
The same furniture, the same
American smell.

410
00:57:26,613 --> 00:57:30,208
- What'ùs an American smell?
- I don't know... you sense it.

411
00:57:30,618 --> 00:57:33,451
Do you like the smell of Russians
best, or Americans?

412
00:57:33,831 --> 00:57:38,268
Leave me alone! I don't know
anything about politics.

413
00:57:40,756 --> 00:57:41,791
<i>The tropics.</i>

414
00:57:44,553 --> 00:57:45,588
<i>Backward countries...</i>

415
00:57:47,223 --> 00:57:48,258
<i>... where you kill animals...</i>

416
00:57:48,600 --> 00:57:50,795
<i>... fish and sunbathe.</i>

417
00:57:51,729 --> 00:57:54,880
<i>And there: "the beautiful
Cuban seÒorita"!</i>

418
00:57:56,694 --> 00:58:00,289
<i>"I'll ever fear anything again",
Macomber said to Wilson.</i>

419
00:58:00,658 --> 00:58:03,968
<i>"Something happened inside me when
I saw the first buffalo.</i>

420
00:58:04,329 --> 00:58:08,959
<i>"Like a dam bursting.
It was pure excitement."</i>

421
00:58:10,045 --> 00:58:13,196
<i>As if chasing a buffalo would
conquer fear.</i>

422
00:58:14,426 --> 00:58:17,782
<i>Anyway, there are no buffaloes
in Cuba.</i>

423
00:58:18,598 --> 00:58:22,352
<i>He conquered fear of death, but
couldn't stand fear of life...</i>

424
00:58:23,020 --> 00:58:25,534
<i>...at a time when the world was
beginning to get too big.</i>

425
00:58:27,943 --> 00:58:29,740
Why did you go away?

426
00:58:30,071 --> 00:58:32,027
You were amusing yourself.

427
00:58:33,450 --> 00:58:34,678
Do you mind?

428
00:58:37,539 --> 00:58:39,211
You don't care.

429
00:58:39,709 --> 00:58:41,427
You don't care about me.

430
00:58:41,711 --> 00:58:45,386
About anything.

431
00:58:49,346 --> 00:58:52,861
This is Hemingway's private study.

432
00:58:53,351 --> 00:58:56,787
He could always be found at
this typewriter.

433
00:58:57,190 --> 00:58:59,704
He never sat down to write.

434
00:59:00,027 --> 00:59:05,055
He'd get up very early and work
till 11 or 11.30.

435
00:59:05,534 --> 00:59:09,493
Few people were allowed into this
room. I was one of them.

436
00:59:09,873 --> 00:59:13,309
I would move about very quietly...

437
00:59:19,219 --> 00:59:20,447
<i>Rene Villarreal.</i>

438
00:59:20,721 --> 00:59:24,191
<i>He was a guttersnipe when
Hemingway found him.</i>

439
00:59:25,060 --> 00:59:26,857
<i>I read that somewhere.</i>

440
00:59:27,313 --> 00:59:30,828
<i>He moulded him to his need:
Faithful servant and great lord.</i>

441
00:59:32,736 --> 00:59:37,491
<i>Colonialist and Gunga Din. Hemingway
must have been insufferable.</i>

442
00:59:41,915 --> 00:59:46,625
<i>This was his refuge, his tower,
his tropical island.</i>

443
00:59:49,884 --> 00:59:52,193
<i>Big game hunting, American
furniture...</i>

444
00:59:52,637 --> 00:59:57,233
<i>... Spanish photos, books in English,
a bullfight poster...</i>

445
00:59:57,894 --> 01:00:00,283
<i>Cuba never really interested him.</i>

446
01:00:01,232 --> 01:00:06,431
<i>It was his refuge, guest house,
base for fishing in the Gulf Stream.</i>

447
01:02:03,517 --> 01:02:05,587
ROUND TABLE: LITERATURE
AND UNDERDEVELOPMENT

448
01:02:05,853 --> 01:02:08,492
Culture in an underdeveloped
country...

449
01:02:08,816 --> 01:02:11,967
...is the sometimes painful
and costly operation...

450
01:02:13,947 --> 01:02:18,065
...by which people become aware of
the possibility...

451
01:02:18,495 --> 01:02:21,328
...of changing social conditions...

452
01:02:21,749 --> 01:02:23,740
...writing their own history...

453
01:02:24,044 --> 01:02:27,832
...and select the most fertile
of their traditions...

